   "source": [
    "# 19. How do you measure the accuracy of a Clustering Algorithm?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "70270cf8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Clustering is unsupervised, so measuring “accuracy” isn’t as straightforward as classification. There’s no single accuracy metric—you evaluate it using different techniques depending on whether you have ground truth labels or not.\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ 1. When TRUE labels are available (External Evaluation)\n",
    "\n",
    "You compare cluster assignments with actual labels:\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Adjusted Rand Index (ARI)\n",
    "Measures similarity between predicted clusters and true labels\n",
    "Range: -1 to 1 (1 = perfect match)\n",
    "🔹 Normalized Mutual Information (NMI)\n",
    "Measures shared information between clusters and labels\n",
    "Range: 0 to 1\n",
    "🔹 Accuracy (after label mapping)\n",
    "Map cluster labels to true labels (since cluster IDs are arbitrary)\n",
    "✅ 2. When NO labels are available (Internal Evaluation)\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the most common case 👇\n",
    "\n",
    "🔥 Silhouette Score (Most important)\n",
    "\n",
    "Where:\n",
    "\n",
    "a = average distance within the same cluster\n",
    "b = average distance to nearest cluster\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Range: -1 to 1\n",
    "\n",
    "+1 → well separated clusters\n",
    "0 → overlapping clusters\n",
    "-1 → wrong clustering\n",
    "🔹 Davies-Bouldin Index (DBI)\n",
    "Measures cluster similarity\n",
    "Lower value = better clustering\n",
    "🔹 Calinski-Harabasz Index\n",
    "Ratio of between-cluster dispersion to within-cluster dispersion\n",
    "Higher value = better\n",
    "✅ 3. Other Practical Methods\n",
    "🔹 Elbow Method\n",
    "Used to find optimal number of clusters (k)\n",
    "🔹 Visual Inspection\n",
    "Use plots (2D/3D via PCA, t-SNE)\n",
    "🎯 Interview-Ready Answer (Short)\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 “Clustering accuracy is measured using internal metrics like Silhouette Score, Davies-Bouldin Index, and Calinski-Harabasz when labels are not available, and external metrics like Adjusted Rand Index and Normalized Mutual Information when ground truth labels exist.”\n",
    "\n",
    "🔥 Pro Tip (Very Important)\n",
    "No single metric is perfect\n",
    "Always use multiple metrics + visualization"
   ]
  },
